            The IAEA/WHO joint report (2005) estimated approximately 4,000
            eventual deaths among those most exposed. Greenpeace and some
            independent researchers estimate far higher numbers. The methodology
            dispute is itself worth reading about.
          </span>
        </aside>
      </article>

      <!-- BHOPAL -->
      <article class="event" id="event-bhopal">
        <header>
          <h3><time datetime="1984-12-03">3 December 1984</time> — Bhopal</h3>
        </header>
        <p>
          The Union Carbide pesticide plant in Bhopal, India, released
          approximately 40 tonnes of methyl isocyanate gas into a densely
          populated area. Safety systems at the plant had been documented as
          failing for months. Cost-cutting had disabled or degraded multiple
          backup systems. Local management knew. The signal — profitable
          operation, schedule, cost reduction — drowned out the mechanism.
          Immediate death toll estimates range from 3,800 to over 15,000.
          Long-term health impacts continue to affect the surrounding
          population.
        </p>
